---
import ProjectLayout from '../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---
<ProjectLayout
  title="Who Pays to Park? Mapping Tel Aviv's Parking Equity by Neighborhood"
  year="2023"
  category="Urban Policy Analysis · Cartography"
  tools={['Python', 'GeoPandas', 'QGIS', 'Choropleth Mapping', 'Spatial Join']}
>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Overview</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        Tel Aviv's curbside parking is divided into three categories: blue-and-white paid zones,
        free white-line spaces, and newly introduced grey regulated areas. The city's ongoing
        rollout of paid parking is politically charged — the distribution of who absorbs parking costs
        maps closely onto neighborhood demographics and proximity to the city center.
      </p>
      <p>
        This analysis joined parking space inventories to neighborhood boundaries, computing
        the share of paid versus free parking for each neighborhood across the city. Rather than
        framing it as a technical inventory, the maps were designed to answer a policy question:
        is the burden of paid parking falling equitably, or is it concentrated in particular parts
        of the city?
      </p>
      <p>
        Multiple palette and classification variants were produced for different audiences — detailed
        graduated maps for technical review, and simplified three-color versions for committee
        presentations. The maps revealed stark spatial variation: central neighborhoods are
        predominantly paid, while peripheral neighborhoods retain large shares of free curbside access.
        This portrait underpins ongoing policy discussions about the pace and geography of further
        pricing rollout.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Maps — Parking Type by Neighborhood</h2>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/parking-blue-white.png`}
      alt="Choropleth map showing percentage of blue-and-white paid parking by Tel Aviv neighborhood"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      Share of blue-and-white (paid) parking spaces by neighborhood. Darker shading indicates higher
      proportion of paid curbside.
    </p>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/parking-free-neighborhood.png`}
      alt="Choropleth map showing percentage of free parking by Tel Aviv neighborhood"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      Share of free (unpaid) parking by neighborhood — the inverse of the paid parking distribution,
      highlighting which areas retain the most free curbside access.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Methods</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        Parking space data was sourced from the municipal parking inventory, containing each
        space's type (blue/white, white, grey) and location. Spaces were spatially joined to
        neighborhood polygons using GeoPandas, and summary statistics — total spaces, spaces by
        type, and type shares — were computed per neighborhood.
      </p>
      <p>
        Choropleth maps were produced in QGIS using Jenks natural-breaks classification for the
        technical variants and manual breaks for the simplified committee versions. Multiple color
        palettes were tested for perceptual clarity and accessibility, with the selected palettes
        validated for color-vision deficiency compatibility.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

</ProjectLayout>
